  "articleSummary": "The article argues that the Single‑Responsibility Principle (SRP) is useful only when applied with judgment, warning that “Single‑Purpose People” mistake “small” for “cohesive” and over‑fragment code into countless tiny files and functions. It illustrates how obsessive adherence to SRP—especially in React/Redux‑style architectures—creates file‑system shrapnel, tangled dependencies, brittle tests, and massive cognitive and velocity costs for developers. The piece is a critical, rant‑like analysis aimed at software engineers, architects, and team leads who value pragmatic modularity over needless perfection, using metaphors of “violence” and “Rube‑Goldberg” code to frame the problem.",
